{"title_page": "August F. Bronner", "text_new": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = August F. Bronner\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = 1835 <!-- {{birth date|1831|07|28}} -->\n|death_date    = October 31, 1893<!-- {{death date and age|1908|01|14|1831|07|28}} -->\n|birth_place   = [[Germany]]\n|death_place   = [[New Jersey]]\n|placeofburial = [[Fairmount Cemetery (Newark, New Jersey)|Fairmount Cemetery]], [[Newark, New Jersey]]\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = [[Private (rank)|Private]]\n|unit          ={{Flagicon|New York|1778}} Battery C, [[1st Battalion New York Volunteer Light Artillery|1st Battalion, New York Volunteer Light Artillery]]\n|battles       = [[Battle of White Oak Swamp]]<br>[[Battle of Malvern Hill]]\n|awards        ={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\nPrivate '''August Frederick Bronner''' (1835 to October 31, 1893)<ref name=\"Jersey\">{{Cite web |url=http://newjerseycivilwargravestones.org/view.php?id=9740 |title=August F. Bronner |accessdate=27 September 2013 |publisher=New Jersey Civil War Gravestones}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Bronner received the United States' highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action during the [[Battle of White Oak Swamp]] in Virginia and the [[Battle of Malvern Hill]] also in [[Virginia]] on June 30, 1862 and July 1, 1862.<ref name=\"History\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.history.army.mil/html/moh/civwaral.html |title=Civil War (A-L) Medal of Honor Recipients |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"CMOHS\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.cmohs.org/recipient-detail/155/bronner-august-f.php |title=Bronner, August F. |accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBronner was born in Germany around 1835. He died on 31 October 1893. His remains are interred at the Fairmount Cemetery, Newark.<ref name=\"Jersey\"/>\n\n==Medal of Honor citation==\n{{quotation|Continued to fight after being severely wounded.<ref name=\"History\"/><ref name=\"CMOHS\"/>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n*[[List of American Civil War Medal of Honor recipients: A\u2013F]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bronner, August F.}}\n[[Category:1835 births]]\n[[Category:1893 deaths]]\n[[Category:German-born Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People of New York (state) in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:Union Army officers]]\n[[Category:United States Army Medal of Honor recipients]]\n[[Category:American Civil War recipients of the Medal of Honor]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military person\n|name          = August F. Bronner\n|image         = \n|birth_date    = 1835 <!-- {{birth date|1831|07|28}} -->\n|death_date    = October 31, 1893<!-- {{death date and age|1908|01|14|1831|07|28}} -->\n|birth_place   = [[Germany]]\n|death_place   = [[New Jersey]]\n|placeofburial = [[Fairmount Cemetery (Newark, New Jersey)|Fairmount Cemetery]], [[Newark, New Jersey]]\n|allegiance    ={{flag|United States of America|1861}}\n|branch        ={{army|USA}}\n|serviceyears  = \n|rank          = [[Private (rank)|Private]]\n|unit          ={{Flagicon|New York}} Company C, 1st New York Artillery\n|battles       = [[Battle of White Oak Swamp]]<br>[[Battle of Malvern Hill]]\n|awards        ={{Flagicon image|Medal of Honor ribbon.svg}} [[Medal of Honor]]\n}}\n\nPrivate '''August Frederick Bronner''' (1835 to October 31, 1893)<ref name=\"Jersey\">{{Cite web |url=http://newjerseycivilwargravestones.org/view.php?id=9740 |title=August F. Bronner |accessdate=27 September 2013 |publisher=New Jersey Civil War Gravestones}}</ref> was a [[Germany|German]] soldier who fought in the [[American Civil War]]. Bronner received the United States' highest award for bravery during combat, the [[Medal of Honor]], for his action d